I used an audiobook series to give myself guided CBT out of my own volition (no therapist, just me and the tapes and material alongside the tapes). It freaking works man. After doing the cognitive part of CBT for a little while I really started to notice some changes. The classic negative thinking that comes from SAD starts becoming less and less powerful as you do the assignments that are given to you each session. And the cognitive assignments aren't even hard. It just took me like 30 mins each day to complete them.
 

 I used to be really anxious in the past, not being able to walk out of my own home without being terribly anxious, to someone who can pretty much function quite well socially in general.
 

 I actually haven't done much of the behavioural portion of the therapy. That's because I slacked off towards the end but also because I lost some motivation to keep going. Also, the behavioural part is a bit scary, obviously, because you're starting to purposely put yourself in anxiety provoking scenarios. I should really pick the therapy back up and destroy those final bits of SAD with the behavioural portion of it. 
 

 Tldr: to me it works wonders, sometimes can't believe how well it has worked for me

Hi all I'd like some input on my situation. From what I see most everyone here is of a similar age group which is nice, so hearing input from likeminded individuals of nearly the same age is nice.
 

 So I'm 17, and have been worrying about quite a few things in relation to my future. I've narrowed it down to around three topics that trigger my anxiety/depression/whatever the most. Those are:
 

 1. Fear due to not knowing what my future holds, no drive of what to do as a profession, etc
 2. Being scared I will not get married before ~30, which is a life goal of mine (if possible without rushing anything, but my main fear lies in just not finding someone who loves me back). 
 3. Being "locked" in my current social situation, not doing anything meaningful, or having anything to look back on.
 

 The thing that is tricky is each of these things happens to be rooted in another, leading to a sort of "feedback loop". Because a solution for one thing presents a problem for another. For example, let's choose #2. When it comes to finding someone, let away marrying them, that requires being social, confident, etc. Which are all things I struggle with. That said, I am making an effort to change that, but my opportunities are limited due to me going to a small school, and having a hard time knowing where to go to find new friends IRL. Online it's much less of an issue. 
 

 Lately, I've just been waking up every day feeling sad, lonely, and all of those other buzzwords that I won't list LOL. Even sleep isn't a break anymore, as I tend to dream about my anxieties. It just feels like everywhere I look, and every solution listed, there is a barrier for one reason or another. If anyone wants to talk, I'm happy to go into more detail, but that's the brunt of it.

One idea that I've come up with is that when it comes to more basic things like your own and others' health, safety, privacy, money and finances, and a few other things that I'm not thinking of, fear and anxiety is helpful as it can get you to significantly consider the negative impacts your decisions can have in those areas. This way we do not overlook large damages that we might inflict on ourselves and other people. However, when those more fundamental things are not at much risk, I think that fear and anxiety often does get us to be too caught up in the potential bad outcomes, when they are not really too too bad in a larger perspective. Fear and anxiety can blow these negatives out of proportion. So, in my view, it is very useful to get yourself to always try to have a perspective where you can more accurately weigh is really important and what is not so important in the grander scheme of things. Something to note is that this is just an idea I have come up with recently but I haven't really tested it or put it into much use.

A question for people, if they had similar experiences. Parents that seem to want to be/are permissive and let you try things out for yourself, but never took an interest in showing you things? And where the location doing anything by yourself extremely difficult. 
 

 I lived out on the country as a kid. The nearest town with anything to do in would take me nearly an hour to reach on bike, exhausted. Always wished I could go to the pool or visit the library, explore the place and see what it had to offer. It made it incredibly difficult to get any real social experiences, and it kinda added up over the years. 
 

 They would sign me up for stuff like a scout's club or kid's gymnastics (early years ofc), but never really ask me what I actually had an interest in doing. It was always presented as "Those are the options.", at least that was the impression kid me got. So I internalized that there was never anything to do, or anyone to be with.
 

 Then imagine my dismay when I recently learned there were all kinds of cool clubs kid me would have loved in the other town over. 20 minutes away in all. Computer club, taekwondo, etc.

Hi, I'm new to this Discord group. I'm not 100% sure I have social anxiety; e.g. I'm okay with 1-on-1 conversations, generally don't feel nervous and don't dread speaking in front of people. However, I struggle a lot with channeling my thoughts and it takes a VERY long for me to form sentences. This may sound weird, but e.g. when talking to my wife, I often just stop talking mid-sentence for 5-10 seconds to figure out what I want to say next. She understands and it's fine. However, when talking to others my mind I don't usually have this luxury so my mind often draws a blank, I just don't know what to say and I get very nervous/anxious, e.g. sweating, shivering, trembling voice, face gets red. I partially deal with this by being extremely prepared (as in, in work meetings I will often just read bullet points I put down on a text file beforehand). Whenever any kind of improvisation is needed though I just can't keep up. It's not anxious > mind draws a blank, it's mind draws a blank > anxious. Once there's a 2-3sec gap where I can't think of what to say next, the anxiety kicks in and there's just no way for me to save things. Worse in larger groups of people because I feel the standard is higher and everything I say must be spot-on and relevant. Just curious if anyone has had any similar experiences?
